["mesh:D000242"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cAMP", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9998046159744263, "span": {"begin": 632, "end": 636}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002784"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cholesterol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9994966983795166, "span": {"begin": 744, "end": 755}}, {"id": ["mesh:D013256"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "steroid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9992555975914001, "span": {"begin": 769, "end": 776}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "granulosa cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8692624568939209, "span": {"begin": 810, "end": 825}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9945494532585144, "span": {"begin": 919, "end": 928}}], "text": "Increased Luteinizing hormone/ Follicle-stimulating hormone (LH/FSH) levels and resulting increased estradiol production in ovaries have been studied in laboratory mammals by addition of hormones (Sashida and Johnson 1976; Spears et al. 1998; Murray et al. 2008). &nbsp;In vitro studies isolating ovarian follicles have been useful in isolating the essentiality of gonadotropins by selective addition (Spears et al. 1998; Murray et al. 2008). &nbsp;Luteinizing hormone binds to receptors on the surface of theca cells, while follicle-stimulating hormone binds to receptors on granulosa cells, cueing cyclic adenosine monophosphate (cAMP) signalling cascades in each cell that results in increased production of enzymes needed for conversion of cholesterol precursor to steroid compounds. &nbsp;Theca cells and granulosa cells are responsible for different enzyme-catalyzed reaction steps resulting in the generation of estradiol.", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 16:21:17 +0000 2026"}